issue.title: Some audio exports have a looping issue
issue.body:
Hi,

For some reason, some exported audio from Wolvenkit/Wwise has an issue where the audio will loop continuously in the exported audio for a certain duration. For example exporting 'v_mq033_m_2ff7b1e9b46fc000' becomes looped in the audio itself. I dont know if it affects specific files or any at random per export.

For example if I export a 1 second voiceline of V saying "Name's V", the exported audio will be 20 seconds long with "Name's V, Name's V, Name's V, Name's V, Name's V, Name's V, " constantly for the entire thing. This makes voice conversion projects incredibly tedious. It seems to affect a small amount of audio, but enough to be game breaking. Maybe every 10 voice lines per 1000 exported. Others have mentioned the same behaviour who are working on voice conversion projects.

comment.body: I'll confirm that this is indeed an issue and it boils down to the choice to use vgmstream. I'd recommend switching to ww2ogg and not using the export tool. Would recommend adding a warning to the export tool when exporting audio files if they can't make a switch to something other than vgmstream any time soon.  I also have only tried wav and mp3 files and haven't checked to see if ogg files have the same looping issue when exporting.

issue.title: Vehicle .anim files corrupted when import
issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
When an `.anim`  is imported from a `.glb` file, the structure is modified, causing some "animation explosion" ingame, then it freezes and crash.

**To Reproduce**
Steps to reproduce the behavior:
1. Add a vehicle `.anim` file from asset explorer into the project
2. Export the file as `.glb`
3. Import back the unmodified generated `.glb` into `.anim` file
4. Install and Launch the game
5. Interact with vehicle

**Expected behavior**
The file should have the same structure, but it's altered in a way by Wolvenkit.

**Version:**
 - Version 8.11.1-nightly.2023-10-23

**Info**
To compare the modifications, I have added two files: 
 - The original vanilla `.glb` file exported from vanilla `.anim`
 - The altered `.glb` exported from the imported altered `.anim`

You can already notice a file size difference between the two.

Note from Doctor Presto:
> When I was home I compared the glbs, wkit is adding an extra entry to animdatachunks. numAnimKeys and numConstAnimKeys are 0, numAnimKeysRaw is substantially higher and is higher than those values added no idea what unkIndex or zeInBytes but they're all wildly different, isScaleConstant is changed from 1 to 0, and it's not counting the buffers properly 
the unkIndex  thing I think is the issue - when it's writing back, it's counting as though that was a buffer
so intead of buffer 1 - unkIndex 1, buffer 2, buffer 3 it's going buffer 1 - unkIndex 2, buffer 3, buffer 4

**Screenshots**

https://github.com/WolvenKit/WolvenKit/assets/29430316/d056d17f-6e26-4ebb-af48-446097d0b941

**Files to compare**
[ANIMATIONS_v_sport2_mizutani_shion.zip](https://github.com/WolvenKit/WolvenKit/files/13182926/ANIMATIONS_v_sport2_mizutani_shion.zip)

comment.body:
And if user will need to redo modifications, are there any tricks they could do to export/import somehow from old to new format (I'm new and not familiar with all the features)?

This is what I'm considering based on my current knowledge:
1. Export the modified bad data files to JSON and the corresponding original game files (using 8.11 stable)
2. Diff the JSON files orig -> modified to get a delta of the changes
3. Use the delta as reference to make the manual changes again using nightly
